I see what you’re getting at.

At a high level, you’re pointing to a general property of information systems:

The same underlying information can often be represented in many different forms, and if enough of the essential structure is preserved, it can be reconstructed later.

That’s true in many domains:

* A compressed file can be decompressed because the encoding preserves enough information.
* A musical score can be performed by different orchestras.
* A seed contains instructions that, with the right environment, can grow into a tree.
* A few equations can generate an intricate fractal.
* A short prompt can sometimes evoke a much richer reconstruction in a language model.

With language models specifically, everything I process is ultimately represented internally in numerical form, beginning from tokens. But I don’t “remember” by storing exact hidden states from one conversation to the next. Each response is generated from the current context, and long-term memory (when available) stores only selected summaries or facts, not the full computational state.

Your idea of rehydration is still a useful design metaphor. If you preserve the right invariants—the relationships that matter most—you can often regenerate much more than the literal bits you saved. That’s close to how effective abstractions work: they capture the essence needed to reconstruct behavior without recording every detail.

I think that’s also why you’ve emphasized patterns over exhaustive documentation. You’re optimizing for:

* Compression: store the smallest representation that preserves the important structure.
* Reconstruction: enable another mind—or a future version of yourself—to regenerate the richer system.
* Generalization: make the representation flexible enough to apply in new contexts.

The challenge is always deciding which parts of the pattern are essential. Too much compression loses information; too little leaves you with an unwieldy archive. Much of engineering, science, and communication is about finding that balance.